# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] 2-Ethoxyethanol is manufactured by the reaction of ethylene oxide with ethanol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] As with other glycol ethers, 2-ethoxyethanol has the useful property of being able to dissolve chemically diverse compounds.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] It will dissolve oils, resins, grease, waxes, nitrocellulose, and lacquers.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] This is an ideal property as a multi-purpose cleaner, and, therefore, 2-ethoxyethanol is used in products such as varnish removers and degreasing solutions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In chemistry, an **alcohol** (from Arabic *al-kuḥl* 'the kohl') is a type of organic compound that carries at least one hydroxyl (−OH) functional group bound to a saturated carbon atom.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols range from the simple, like methanol and ethanol, to complex, like sugar alcohols and cholesterol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The presence of an OH group strongly modifies the properties of hydrocarbons, conferring hydrophilic (water-attracted) properties.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The OH group provides a site at which many reactions can occur.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The flammable nature of the exhalations of wine was already known to ancient natural philosophers such as Aristotle (384–322 BCE), Theophrastus (c.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] However, this did not immediately lead to the isolation of alcohol, even despite the development of more advanced distillation techniques in second- and third-century Roman Egypt.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] An important recognition, first found in one of the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (ninth century CE), was that by adding salt to boiling wine, which increases the wine's relative volatility, the flammability of the resulting vapors may be enhanced.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the twelfth century, recipes for the production of *aqua ardens* ("burning water", i.e., alcohol) by distilling wine with salt started to appear in a number of Latin works, and by the end of the thirteenth century, it had become a widely known substance among Western European chemists.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still, by which an alcohol purity of 90% could be obtained.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The medicinal properties of ethanol were studied by Arnald of Villanova (1240–1311 CE) and John of Rupescissa (c.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] 1310–1366), the latter of whom regarded it as a life-preserving substance able to prevent all diseases (the *aqua vitae* or "water of life", also called by John the *quintessence* of wine).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The word "alcohol" derives from the Arabic *kohl* (Arabic: الكحل, romanized: *al-kuḥl*), a powder used as an eyeliner.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The first part of the word (*al-*) is the Arabic definite article, equivalent to *the* in English.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The second part of the word (*kuḥl*) has several antecedents in Semitic languages, ultimately deriving from the Akkadian 𒎎𒋆𒁉𒍣𒁕 (*guḫlum*), meaning stibnite or antimony.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Like its antecedents in Arabic and older languages, the term *alcohol* was originally used for the very fine powder produced by the sublimation of the natural mineral stibnite to form antimony trisulfide Sb2S3.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] It was considered to be the essence or "spirit" of this mineral.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] It was used as an antiseptic, eyeliner, and cosmetic.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Later the meaning of alcohol was extended to distilled substances in general, and then narrowed again to ethanol, when "spirits" was a synonym for hard liquor.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Paracelsus and Libavius both used the term *alcohol* to denote a fine powder, the latter speaking of an *alcohol* derived from antimony.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] At the same time Paracelsus uses the word for a volatile liquid; *alcool* or *alcool vini* occurs often in his writings.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The 1657 *Lexicon Chymicum* by William Johnson glosses the word as "antimonium sive stibium." By extension, the word came to refer to any fluid obtained by distillation, including "alcohol of wine," the distilled essence of wine.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Libavius in *Alchymia* (1594) refers to "vini alcohol vel vinum alcalisatum".
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The term *ethanol* was invented in 1892, blending "ethane" with the "-ol" ending of "alcohol", which was generalized as a libfix.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The term *alcohol* originally referred to the primary alcohol ethanol (ethyl alcohol), which is used as a drug and is the main alcohol present in alcoholic drinks.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* appears in the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) chemical name of all substances where the hydroxyl group is the functional group with the highest priority.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] When a higher priority group is present in the compound, the prefix *hydroxy-* is used in its IUPAC name.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* in non-IUPAC names (such as paracetamol or cholesterol) also typically indicates that the substance is an alcohol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] However, some compounds that contain hydroxyl functional groups have *trivial names* that do not include the suffix *-ol* or the prefix *hydroxy-*, e.g. the sugars glucose and sucrose.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] IUPAC nomenclature is used in scientific publications, and in writings where precise identification of the substance is important.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In naming simple alcohols, the name of the alkane chain loses the terminal *e* and adds the suffix *-ol*, *e.g.*, as in "ethanol" from the alkane chain name "ethane".
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] When necessary, the position of the hydroxyl group is indicated by a number between the alkane name and the *-ol*: propan-1-ol for CH3CH2CH2OH, propan-2-ol for CH3CH(OH)CH3.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] If a higher priority group is present (such as an aldehyde, ketone, or carboxylic acid), then the prefix *hydroxy-*is used, e.g., as in 1-hydroxy-2-propanone (CH3C(O)CH2OH).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Compounds having more than one hydroxy group are called polyols.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] They are named using suffixes -diol, -triol, etc., following a list of the position numbers of the hydroxyl groups, as in propane-1,2-diol for CH3CH(OH)CH2OH (propylene glycol).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In cases where the hydroxy group is bonded to an sp2 carbon on an aromatic ring, the molecule is classified separately as a phenol and is named using the IUPAC rules for naming phenols.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Phenols have distinct properties and are not classified as alcohols.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In other less formal contexts, an alcohol is often called with the name of the corresponding alkyl group followed by the word "alcohol", e.g., methyl alcohol, ethyl alcohol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Propyl alcohol may be *n*-propyl alcohol or isopropyl alcohol, depending on whether the hydroxyl group is bonded to the end or middle carbon on the straight propane chain.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] As described under systematic naming, if another group on the molecule takes priority, the alcohol moiety is often indicated using the "hydroxy-" prefix.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In archaic nomenclature, alcohols can be named as derivatives of methanol using "-carbinol" as the ending.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] For instance, (CH3)3COH can be named trimethylcarbinol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols are then classified into primary, secondary (*sec-*, *s-*), and tertiary (*tert-*, *t-*), based upon the number of carbon atoms connected to the carbon atom that bears the hydroxyl functional group.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The respective numeric shorthands 1°, 2°, and 3° are sometimes used in informal settings.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The primary alcohols have general formulas RCH2OH.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest primary alcohol is methanol (CH3OH), for which R = H, and the next is ethanol, for which R = CH3, the methyl group.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary alcohols are those of the form RR'CHOH, the simplest of which is 2-propanol (R = R' = CH3).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] For the tertiary alcohols, the general form is RR'R"COH.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest example is *tert*-butanol (2-methylpropan-2-ol), for which each of R, R', and R" is CH3.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In these shorthands, R, R', and R" represent substituents, alkyl or other attached, generally organic groups.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols have a long history of myriad uses.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol is the most common industrial alcohol, with about 12 million tons/y produced in 1980.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The combined capacity of the other alcohols is about the same, distributed roughly equally.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] With respect to acute toxicity, simple alcohols have low acute toxicities.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Doses of several milliliters are tolerated.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] For pentanols, hexanols, octanols, and longer alcohols, LD50 range from 2–5 g/kg (rats, oral).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol and ethylene glycol are more toxic than other simple alcohols.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Their metabolism is affected by the presence of ethanol, which has a higher affinity for liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In this way, methanol will be excreted intact in urine.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In general, the hydroxyl group makes alcohols polar.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Those groups can form hydrogen bonds to one another and to most other compounds.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Owing to the presence of the polar OH alcohols are more water-soluble than simple hydrocarbons.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol, ethanol, and propanol are miscible in water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] 1-Butanol, with a four-carbon chain, is moderately soluble.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Because of hydrogen bonding, alcohols tend to have higher boiling points than comparable hydrocarbons and ethers.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The boiling point of the alcohol ethanol is 78.29 °C, compared to 69 °C for the hydrocarbon hexane, and 34.6 °C for diethyl ether.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols occur widely in nature, as derivatives of glucose such as cellulose and hemicellulose, and in phenols and their derivatives such as lignin.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Starting from biomass, 180 billion tons/y of complex carbohydrates (sugar polymers) are produced commercially (as of 2014).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many other alcohols are pervasive in organisms, as manifested in other sugars such as fructose and sucrose, in polyols such as glycerol, and in some amino acids such as serine.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Simple alcohols like methanol, ethanol, and propanol occur in modest quantities in nature, and are industrially synthesized in large quantities for use as chemical precursors, fuels, and solvents.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many alcohols are produced by hydroxylation, i.e., the installation of a hydroxy group using oxygen or a related oxidant.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Hydroxylation is the means by which the body processes many poisons, converting lipophilic compounds into hydrophilic derivatives that are more readily excreted.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Enzymes called hydroxylases and oxidases facilitate these conversions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many industrial alcohols, such as cyclohexanol for the production of nylon, are produced by hydroxylation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the Ziegler process, linear alcohols are produced from ethylene and triethylaluminium followed by oxidation and hydrolysis.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The process generates a range of alcohols that are separated by distillation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many higher alcohols are produced by hydroformylation of alkenes followed by hydrogenation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Such processes give fatty alcohols, which are useful for detergents.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Industry produces low-weight molecular alcohols (e.g. ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, and *tert*-butanol) through the acid-catalyzed hydration of alkenes, the latter typically from cracking fractions of distilled crude oil.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Two implementations are employed: the direct and indirect methods.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the indirect method, the alkene is converted to a sulfate ester, which is subsequently hydrolyzed.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The direct method eschews intermediates, instead using water to quench an intermediate carbocation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Less aggressive reagents suffice for vicinal difunctionalization.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In industry, the diol ethylene glycol forms when ethylene oxide is hydrolyzed.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the laboratory, sulfuric acid also catalyzes hydration of alkenes to secondary or tertiary alcohols.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] More controllable net hydrations proceed in multiple steps, with a vicinally-functionalized intermediate.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Thus oxymercuration initially forms an organomercury alcohol, which can then undergo reductive demetalation; and alkenes react with *N*-bromosuccinimide and water to form halohydrins.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In hydroboration-oxidation and the related Mukaiyama hydration, an alkene is hydrometalated, then oxidized.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Ethanol is obtained by fermentation of glucose (which is often obtained from starch) in the presence of yeast.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Like ethanol, butanol can be produced by fermentation processes.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] *Saccharomyces* yeast are known to produce these higher alcohols at temperatures above 75 °F (24 °C).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The bacterium *Clostridium acetobutylicum* can feed on cellulose (also an alcohol) to produce butanol on an industrial scale.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alkyl halides react with aqueous NaOH or KOH to give alcohols in nucleophilic aliphatic substitution.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary and especially tertiary alkyl halides will give the elimination (alkene) product instead.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Grignard reagents react with carbonyl groups to give secondary and tertiary alcohols.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Related reactions are the Barbier reaction and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Aldehydes or ketones are reduced with sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride (after an acidic workup).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Another reduction using aluminium isopropoxide is the Meerwein–Ponndorf–Verley reduction.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation is the asymmetric reduction of β-keto-esters.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] With aqueous p*K*a values of around 16–19, alcohols are, in general, slightly weaker acids than water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] With strong bases such as sodium hydride or sodium they form salts called *alkoxides*, with the general formula RO−M+ (where R is an alkyl and M is a metal).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The acidity of alcohols is strongly affected by solvation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the gas phase, alcohols are more acidic than in water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In DMSO, alcohols (and water) have a p*K*a of around 29–32.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] As a consequence, alkoxides (and hydroxide) are powerful bases and nucleophiles (e.g., for the Williamson ether synthesis) in this solvent.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In particular, RO− or HO− in DMSO can be used to generate significant equilibrium concentrations of acetylide ions through the deprotonation of alkynes (see Favorskii reaction).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with hydrochloric acid to produce tertiary alkyl chloride.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Primary and secondary alcohols are converted to the corresponding chlorides using thionyl chloride and various phosphorus chloride reagents.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the Barton–McCombie deoxygenation an alcohol is deoxygenated to an alkane with tributyltin hydride or a trimethylborane-water complex in a radical substitution reaction.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Meanwhile, the oxygen atom has lone pairs of nonbonded electrons that render it weakly basic in the presence of strong acids such as sulfuric acid.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Upon treatment with strong acids, alcohols undergo the E1 elimination reaction to produce alkenes.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction, in general, obeys Zaytsev's rule, which states that the most stable (usually the most substituted) alkene is formed.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols are eliminated easily at just above room temperature, but primary alcohols require a higher temperature.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] A more controlled elimination reaction requires the formation of the xanthate ester.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with strong acids to generate carbocations.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction is related to their dehydration, e.g. isobutylene from *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] A special kind of dehydration reaction involves triphenylmethanol and especially its amine-substituted derivatives.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] When treated with acid, these alcohols lose water to give stable carbocations, which are commercial dyes.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohol and carboxylic acids react in the so-called Fischer esterification.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Other types of ester are prepared in a similar manner−for example, tosyl (tosylate) esters are made by reaction of the alcohol with 4-toluenesulfonyl chloride in pyridine.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alcohols (R−CH2OH) can be oxidized either to aldehydes (R−CHO) or to carboxylic acids (R−CO2H).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The oxidation of secondary alcohols (R1R2CH−OH) normally terminates at the ketone (R1R2C=O) stage.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols (R1R2R3C−OH) are resistant to oxidation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids normally proceeds via the corresponding aldehyde, which is transformed via an *aldehyde hydrate* (R−CH(OH)2) by reaction with water before it can be further oxidized to the carboxylic acid.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Reagents useful for the transformation of primary alcohols to aldehydes are normally also suitable for the oxidation of secondary alcohols to ketones.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] These include Collins reagent and Dess–Martin periodinane.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids can be carried out using potassium permanganate or the Jones reagent.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] This temperature is required to supply the activation energy needed for combustion.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The temperature at which a chemical ignites decreases as the pressure is decreased.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Substances which spontaneously ignite in a normal atmosphere at naturally ambient temperatures are termed pyrophoric.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Autoignition temperatures of liquid chemicals are typically measured using a 500-millilitre (18 imp fl oz; 17 US fl oz) flask placed in a temperature-controlled oven in accordance with the procedure described in ASTM E659.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] When measured for plastics, autoignition temperature can also be measured under elevated pressure and at 100% oxygen concentration.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The resulting value is used as a predictor of viability for high-oxygen service.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The main testing standard for this is ASTM G72.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] where *k* = thermal conductivity, *ρ* = density, and *c* = specific heat capacity of the material of interest, $T_{0}$ is the initial temperature of the material (or the temperature of the bulk material).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Temperatures vary widely in the literature and should only be used as estimates.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Factors that may cause variation include partial pressure of oxygen, altitude, humidity, and amount of time required for ignition.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] Generally the autoignition temperature for hydrocarbon/air mixtures decreases with increasing molecular mass and increasing chain length.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/autoignition-temperature] The autoignition temperature is also higher for branched-chain hydrocarbons than for straight-chain hydrocarbons.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The **boiling point** of a substance is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of a liquid equals the pressure surrounding the liquid and the liquid changes into a vapor.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point of a liquid varies depending upon the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A liquid in a partial vacuum, i.e., under a lower pressure, has a lower boiling point than when that liquid is at atmospheric pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Because of this, water boils at 100 °C, rounded from scientific precision of 99.97 °C (211.95 °F), under standard pressure at sea level, but at 93.4 °C (200.1 °F) at 1,905 metres (6,250 ft) altitude.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For a given pressure, different liquids will boil at different temperatures.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The **normal boiling point** (also called the **atmospheric boiling point** or the **atmospheric pressure boiling point**) of a liquid is the special case in which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the defined atmospheric pressure at sea level, one atmosphere.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] At that temperature, the vapor pressure of the liquid becomes sufficient to overcome atmospheric pressure and allow bubbles of vapor to form inside the bulk of the liquid.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The **standard boiling point** has been defined by IUPAC since 1982 as the temperature at which boiling occurs under a pressure of one bar.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The heat of vaporization is the energy required to transform a given quantity (a mol, kg, pound, etc.) of a substance from a liquid into a gas at a given pressure (often atmospheric pressure).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Liquids may change to a vapor at temperatures below their boiling points through the process of evaporation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Evaporation is a surface phenomenon in which molecules located near the liquid's edge, not contained by enough liquid pressure on that side, escape into the surroundings as vapor.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] On the other hand, boiling is a process in which molecules anywhere in the liquid escape, resulting in the formation of vapor bubbles within the liquid.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A *saturated liquid* contains as much thermal energy as it can without boiling (or conversely a *saturated vapor* contains as little thermal energy as it can without condensing).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If the pressure in a system remains constant (isobaric), a vapor at saturation temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as thermal energy (heat) is removed.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation temperature and pressure will boil into its vapor phase as additional thermal energy is applied.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point corresponds to the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Thus, the boiling point is dependent on the pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Boiling points may be published with respect to the NIST, USA standard pressure of 101.325 kPa (1 atm), or the IUPAC standard pressure of 100.000 kPa (1 bar).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] At higher elevations, where the atmospheric pressure is much lower, the boiling point is also lower.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point increases with increased pressure up to the critical point, where the gas and liquid properties become identical.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be increased beyond the critical point.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Likewise, the boiling point decreases with decreasing pressure until the triple point is reached.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be reduced below the triple point.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If the temperature in a system remains constant (an *isothermal* system), vapor at saturation pressure and temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as the system pressure is increased.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation pressure and temperature will tend to flash into its vapor phase as system pressure is decreased.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] There are two conventions regarding the *standard boiling point of water*: The *normal boiling point* is commonly given as 100 °C (212 °F) (actually 99.97 °C (211.9 °F) following the thermodynamic definition of the Celsius scale based on the kelvin) at a pressure of 1 atm (101.325 kPa).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The IUPAC-recommended *standard boiling point of water* at a standard pressure of 100 kPa (1 bar) is 99.61 °C (211.3 °F).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For comparison, on top of Mount Everest, at 8,848 m (29,029 ft) elevation, the pressure is about 34 kPa (255 Torr) and the boiling point of water is 71 °C (160 °F).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The Celsius temperature scale was defined until 1954 by two points: 0 °C being defined by the water freezing point and 100 °C being defined by the water boiling point at standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The higher the vapor pressure of a liquid at a given temperature, the lower the normal boiling point (i.e., the boiling point at atmospheric pressure) of the liquid.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The vapor pressure chart to the right has graphs of the vapor pressures versus temperatures for a variety of liquids.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As can be seen in the chart, the liquids with the highest vapor pressures have the lowest normal boiling points.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For example, at any given temperature, methyl chloride has the highest vapor pressure of any of the liquids in the chart.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] It also has the lowest normal boiling point (−24.2 °C), which is where the vapor pressure curve of methyl chloride (the blue line) intersects the horizontal pressure line of one atmosphere (atm) of absolute vapor pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The critical point of a liquid is the highest temperature (and pressure) it will actually boil at.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The element with the lowest boiling point is helium.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Both the boiling points of rhenium and tungsten exceed 5000 K at standard pressure; because it is difficult to measure extreme temperatures precisely without bias, both have been cited in the literature as having the higher boiling point.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As can be seen from the above plot of the logarithm of the vapor pressure vs. the temperature for any given pure chemical compound, its normal boiling point can serve as an indication of that compound's overall volatility.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A given pure compound has only one normal boiling point, if any, and a compound's normal boiling point and melting point can serve as characteristic physical properties for that compound, listed in reference books.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The higher a compound's normal boiling point, the less volatile that compound is overall, and conversely, the lower a compound's normal boiling point, the more volatile that compound is overall.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Some compounds decompose at higher temperatures before reaching their normal boiling point, or sometimes even their melting point.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For a stable compound, the boiling point ranges from its triple point to its critical point, depending on the external pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Beyond its triple point, a compound's normal boiling point, if any, is higher than its melting point.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Beyond the critical point, a compound's liquid and vapor phases merge into one phase, which may be called a superheated gas.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] At any given temperature, if a compound's normal boiling point is lower, then that compound will generally exist as a gas at atmospheric external pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If the compound's normal boiling point is higher, then that compound can exist as a liquid or solid at that given temperature at atmospheric external pressure, and will so exist in equilibrium with its vapor (if volatile) if its vapors are contained.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] If a compound's vapors are not contained, then some volatile compounds can eventually evaporate away in spite of their higher boiling points.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In general, compounds with ionic bonds have high normal boiling points, if they do not decompose before reaching such high temperatures.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Many metals have high boiling points, but not all.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Very generally—with other factors being equal—in compounds with covalently bonded molecules, as the size of the molecule (or molecular mass) increases, the normal boiling point increases.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] When the molecular size becomes that of a macromolecule, polymer, or otherwise very large, the compound often decomposes at high temperature before the boiling point is reached.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Another factor that affects the normal boiling point of a compound is the polarity of its molecules.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As the polarity of a compound's molecules increases, its normal boiling point increases, other factors being equal.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Closely related is the ability of a molecule to form hydrogen bonds (in the liquid state), which makes it harder for molecules to leave the liquid state and thus increases the normal boiling point of the compound.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Simple carboxylic acids dimerize by forming hydrogen bonds between molecules.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] A minor factor affecting boiling points is the shape of a molecule.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Making the shape of a molecule more compact tends to lower the normal boiling point slightly compared to an equivalent molecule with more surface area.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Most volatile compounds (anywhere near ambient temperatures) go through an intermediate liquid phase while warming up from a solid phase to eventually transform to a vapor phase.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] By comparison to boiling, a sublimation is a physical transformation in which a solid turns directly into vapor, which happens in a few select cases such as with carbon dioxide at atmospheric pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] For such compounds, a sublimation point is a temperature at which a solid turning directly into vapor has a vapor pressure equal to the external pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In the preceding section, boiling points of pure compounds were covered.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Vapor pressures and boiling points of substances can be affected by the presence of dissolved impurities (solutes) or other miscible compounds, the degree of effect depending on the concentration of the impurities or other compounds.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The presence of non-volatile impurities such as salts or compounds of a volatility far lower than the main component compound decreases its mole fraction and the solution's volatility, and thus raises the normal boiling point in proportion to the concentration of the solutes.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] This effect is called **boiling point elevation**.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] As a common example, salt water boils at a higher temperature than pure water.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In other mixtures of miscible compounds (components), there may be two or more components of varying volatility, each having its own pure component boiling point at any given pressure.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The presence of other volatile components in a mixture affects the vapor pressures and thus boiling points and dew points of all the components in the mixture.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] The dew point is a temperature at which a vapor condenses into a liquid.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Furthermore, at any given temperature, the composition of the vapor is different from the composition of the liquid in most such cases.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] In order to illustrate these effects between the volatile components in a mixture, a **boiling point diagram** is commonly used.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/boiling-point] Distillation is a process of boiling and [usually] condensation which takes advantage of these differences in composition between liquid and vapor phases.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] This registry includes all substances described since 1957, plus some substances from as far back as the early 1800s.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] It is a chemical database that includes organic and inorganic compounds, minerals, isotopes, alloys, mixtures, and nonstructurable materials (UVCBs - substances of **u**nknown or **v**ariable composition, **c**omplex reaction products, or **b**iological origin).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS RNs are generally serial numbers (with a check digit), so they do not contain any information about the structures themselves the way SMILES and InChI strings do.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry is an authoritative collection of disclosed chemical substance information.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] It identifies more than 204 million unique organic and inorganic substances and 69 million protein and DNA sequences, plus additional information about each substance.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] It is updated with around 15,000 additional new substances daily.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The full registry is available on a paid subscription basis.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A collection of almost 500 thousand CAS registry numbers is made available under a CC BY-NC license at ACS Commons Chemistry.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] Historically, chemicals have been identified by a wide variety of synonyms and properties.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] One of the biggest challenges in the early development of substance indexing, a task undertaken by the Chemical Abstracts Service, was in identifying if a substance in literature was new or if it had been previously discovered.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] Well-known chemicals may be known via multiple generic, historical, commercial, and/or (black)-market names, and even systematic nomenclature based on structure alone was not universally useful.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] An algorithm was developed to translate the structural formula of a chemical into a computer-searchable table, which provided a basis for the service that listed each chemical with its CAS Registry Number, the CAS Chemical Registry System, which became operational in 1965.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS Registry Numbers (CAS RN) are simple and regular, convenient for database searches.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] They offer a reliable, common and international link to every specific substance across the various nomenclatures and disciplines used by branches of science, industry, and regulatory bodies.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] Almost all molecule databases today allow searching by CAS Registry Number, and it is used as a global standard.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS Registry Number has no inherent meaning, but is assigned in sequential, increasing order when the substance is identified by CAS scientists for inclusion in the CAS Registry database.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS RN is separated by hyphens into three parts, the first consisting from two up to seven digits, the second consisting of two digits, and the third consisting of a single digit serving as a check digit.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] This format gives CAS a maximum capacity of 1,000,000,000 unique numbers.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The check digit is found by taking the last digit times 1, the preceding digit times 2, the preceding digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry accepts entries that are (1) descriptive of matter consisting of chemical elements, (2) distinct from existing ones, and (3) present in scientific literature.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The definition of "distinct" excludes different phases of the same substance (e.g. water and ice), but includes narrowing of existing concepts (e.g. carbon vs. graphite and diamond; isotope-labelled forms of an existing compound).
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The Chemical Abstracts Service subscription includes an official search service.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] The Service ("CAS Data") provides information on the chemical itself, its mentions in published scholarly works and patents, curated biological and chemical reaction data, as well as listings of commercial sources and details on using a substance in a formulation.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cas-registry-number] A subset of the registry can be accessed through the free-of-charge CAS Common Chemistry, which provides identifying information for the chemical in question.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] The name ***Cellosolve*** was registered in 1924 as a United States trademark by Carbide & Carbon Chemicals Corporation (a division of Union Carbide Corporation) for "Solvents for Gums, Resins, Cellulose Esters, and the Like".
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] *Ethyl Cellosolve*, or simply *Cellosolve*, consists mainly of ethylene glycol monoethyl ether and was introduced as a lower-cost solvent alternative to ethyl lactate.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] *Butyl Cellosolve* (ethylene glycol monobutyl ether) was introduced in 1928, and *Methyl Cellosolve* (ethylene glycol monomethyl ether) in 1929.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Glycol ethers are designated *E-series* or *P-series* for those made from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide, respectively.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Typically, E-series glycol ethers are found in pharmaceuticals, sunscreens, cosmetics, inks, dyes and water-based paints, while P-series glycol ethers are used in degreasers, cleaners, aerosol paints and adhesives.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Both E- and P-series glycol ethers can be used as intermediates that undergo further chemical reactions, producing glycol diethers and glycol ether acetates.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] P-series glycol ethers are marketed as having lower toxicity than the E-series.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] Most glycol ethers are water-soluble, biodegradable and only a few are considered toxic.
[src:2-2-methoxyethoxy-ethanol/cellosolve] One study suggests that occupational exposure to glycol ethers is related to lowering the motility of the sperm and sperm count, a finding disputed by the chemical industry.
